available through sparklyr

00:10:16.479 --> 00:10:19.520
to execute queries against this dataset.

00:10:19.520 --> 00:10:20.359
So I can come in here,

00:10:20.359 --> 00:10:21.479
it's gonna use a glimpse,

00:10:21.479 --> 00:10:22.320
you can see here,

00:10:22.320 --> 00:10:23.919
one of the key kind of tells

00:10:23.919 --> 00:10:25.400
that I'm working with remote data

00:10:25.400 --> 00:10:26.679
is that this comes back and says,

00:10:26.679 --> 00:10:27.760
like, I actually don't know

00:10:27.760 --> 00:10:29.359
how many rows are here,

00:10:29.359 --> 00:10:31.320
because I didn't ask that about the data,

00:10:31.320 --> 00:10:33.960
I just took a snapshot of the first few rows

00:10:33.960 --> 00:10:35.479
so that you could gain some visibility.

00:10:35.479 --> 00:10:38.039
So we can see that it's submitting queries

00:10:38.039 --> 00:10:39.960
over to this data connection

00:10:39.960 --> 00:10:40.960
inside of Databricks,

00:10:40.960 --> 00:10:43.400
and building up kind of its understanding

00:10:43.400 --> 00:10:44.640
of what this data looks like.

00:10:44.640 --> 00:10:45.880
And this is kind of much more

00:10:45.880 --> 00:10:48.020
of an agentic style workflow,

00:10:48.020 --> 00:10:49.700
where it's executing some code,

00:10:49.700 --> 00:10:50.919
it's looking at the results,

00:10:50.919 --> 00:10:52.359
it's executing some more code,

00:10:52.359 --> 00:10:53.280
it's looking at the results,

00:10:53.280 --> 00:10:55.840
and then we can kind of see its dialogue here.

00:10:55.840 --> 00:10:56.679
If we go down, it's like,

00:10:56.679 --> 00:10:57.599
okay, I can see this is

00:10:57.599 --> 00:10:59.119
a comprehensive cycling dataset,

00:10:59.880 --> 00:11:00.719
it seems like it's Tour de France data,

00:11:00.719 --> 00:11:02.919
with some rich historical information,

00:11:02.919 --> 00:11:06.080
there's about 250,000 rows,

00:11:06.080 --> 00:11:07.559
there's 106 different editions,

00:11:07.559 --> 00:11:08.799
there's unique stages,

00:11:08.799 --> 00:11:10.559
so here's kind of what I found, right,

00:11:10.559 --> 00:11:11.840
it's giving us some information

00:11:11.840 --> 00:11:13.760
about what it sees in the data.

00:11:13.760 --> 00:11:14.919
And then let's go ahead and say,

00:11:14.919 --> 00:11:17.080
let's see, it gives us some suggestions here,

00:11:17.080 --> 00:11:19.960
let's look at the distribution of ages

00:11:19.960 --> 00:11:22.640
across the Tour de France from 1903 to 2019,

00:11:22.640 --> 00:11:24.299
and how that's evolved.

00:11:24.299 --> 00:11:26.000
So again, it's gonna go through,

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:26.840
write queries,

00:11:26.840 --> 00:11:29.200
and what I'm gonna do now, actually,

00:11:29.200 --> 00:11:30.539
I think I've got this,

00:11:33.640 --> 00:11:37.200
I'm gonna open up our Databricks instance really quickly,

00:11:37.200 --> 00:11:39.760
just because I think it's kind of interesting to see

00:11:41.599 --> 00:11:44.159
if the Wi-Fi's happy, there we go.

00:11:44.159 --> 00:11:45.659
I'll zoom in in just a moment.

00:11:52.400 --> 00:11:53.239
All right.

00:11:54.239 --> 00:11:56.840
So if I come into Databricks,

00:11:56.840 --> 00:11:58.559
and I look at the cluster that I've connected to,

00:11:58.559 --> 00:12:00.000
so if I look, let me zoom in.

00:12:01.520 --> 00:12:03.400
All right, let's go one more, there we go.

00:12:03.400 --> 00:12:04.640
Okay, so if I come to compute,

00:12:04.640 --> 00:12:06.159
I'm connected to this cluster,

00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:08.780
I can come over here,

00:12:08.780 --> 00:12:13.320
I can look at the driver logs,

00:12:13.320 --> 00:12:15.359
no, I don't need driver logs, what do I need?

00:12:15.359 --> 00:12:16.200
There we go.

00:12:17.719 --> 00:12:19.960
If I look at the SQL queries that are coming in,

00:12:19.960 --> 00:12:21.179
and I expand any of these,

00:12:21.179 --> 00:12:23.700
I can see that these are queries coming

00:12:23.700 --> 00:12:26.820
related to this stages data, right?

00:12:26.820 --> 00:12:28.940
So the formatting here is not super great,

00:12:28.940 --> 00:12:30.099
and here's a bunch of line breaks

00:12:30.099 --> 00:12:31.739
that are just included in plain text,

00:12:31.739 --> 00:12:34.119
but this is the SQL that's being submitted

00:12:34.119 --> 00:12:35.340
for execution by Databricks.

00:12:35.340 --> 00:12:37.739
So Databricks is running all the compute data,

00:12:37.739 --> 00:12:39.580
it's this cluster on Databricks

00:12:39.580 --> 00:12:41.700
that's doing all the calculation for me,

00:12:41.700 --> 00:12:44.239
but it's DataBot that's driving that calculation.

00:12:44.239 --> 00:12:45.580
So I have kind of the best of both worlds.

00:12:45.580 --> 00:12:47.340
I'm able to keep all of my data securely

00:12:47.340 --> 00:12:49.219
in the database that I wanna keep it in.

00:12:49.219 --> 00:12:51.380
Again, this might be BigQuery, it might be Redshift,

00:12:51.380 --> 00:12:53.559
it might be DuckDB, it doesn't really matter.

00:12:53.559 --> 00:12:55.419
The backend is less important here

00:12:55.419 --> 00:12:58.419
than the principle of DataBot and Positron Assistant

00:12:58.419 --> 00:13:01.299
are both very capable of driving analysis

00:13:01.299 --> 00:13:04.859
against remote data without being overly eager

00:13:04.859 --> 00:13:07.780
to pull all that data into your local environment.

00:13:07.780 --> 00:13:11.500
If we come back here into our Positron environment now,

00:13:11.500 --> 00:13:13.419
we can see we've created some plots,

00:13:13.419 --> 00:13:14.979
evolution of writer ages,

00:13:14.979 --> 00:13:17.140
oldest writer, youngest writer, average age.

00:13:17.140 --> 00:13:19.059
So average age has been slightly increasing

00:13:19.900 --> 00:13:21.900
over time, early editions of the tour

00:13:21.900 --> 00:13:26.219
had some fairly old writers by athlete standards.

00:13:26.219 --> 00:13:29.119
I think the oldest writer in the data set's 49 years old.

00:13:30.460 --> 00:13:31.979
And then you can see that the youngest writers

00:13:31.979 --> 00:13:34.099
kind of crept up, young writers now

00:13:34.099 --> 00:13:36.500
are typically in their early 20s.

00:13:38.099 --> 00:13:42.020
So this process of working through and exploring data

00:13:42.020 --> 00:13:45.979
in this sort of interactive AI-assisted way

00:13:45.979 --> 00:13:47.739
doesn't just work with local data,

00:13:47.739 --> 00:13:49.140
which is a lot of what we've kind of seen

00:13:49.140 --> 00:13:51.380
demonstrated at the conference this year,

00:13:51.380 --> 00:13:52.780
but it also works really well

00:13:52.780 --> 00:13:55.500
against these remote data sources.

00:13:55.500 --> 00:13:57.419
Now I want to point out a couple of things

00:13:57.419 --> 00:13:58.239
that I think are significant.

00:13:58.239 --> 00:14:01.539
One is this works really well

00:14:01.539 --> 00:14:03.539
when you're already connected to the data.

00:14:03.539 --> 00:14:05.700
So notice in both cases with both Snowflake

00:14:05.700 --> 00:14:08.500
and with, excuse me, with both Snowflake and Databricks,

00:14:08.500 --> 00:14:10.700
the first thing I did was I created the connection

00:14:10.700 --> 00:14:12.780
to the data myself and then said,

00:14:12.780 --> 00:14:14.479
hey, help me explore this thing.

00:14:15.419 --> 00:14:17.500
That's fine, and you may be well familiar

00:14:18.239 --> 00:14:19.219
with how to establish these connections,

00:14:19.219 --> 00:14:20.659
and in fact, if you're in an environment

00:14:20.659 --> 00:14:22.820
where you're often interacting with remote data,

00:14:22.820 --> 00:14:25.700
you're probably familiar with how to do this.

00:14:25.700 --> 00:14:27.059
But we've been doing some experiments.

00:14:27.059 --> 00:14:30.380
One of my favorite things, about a month ago,

00:14:30.380 --> 00:14:34.059
we just opened up sort of a blank Positron session,

00:14:34.059 --> 00:14:36.659
loaded Databot, we had nothing set up, right?

00:14:36.659 --> 00:14:39.780
I've got a blank session, I've loaded no packages,

00:14:39.780 --> 00:14:43.140
I've loaded no variables into my local environment,

00:14:43.140 --> 00:14:46.659
and I said, hey, I have some data in Databricks,

00:14:46.659 --> 00:14:47.859
I wanna explore it.

00:14:47.859 --> 00:14:50.539
And Databot tried its very hardest to help me.

00:14:50.539 --> 00:14:52.380
It was like, okay, let's connect to Databricks.

00:14:52.380 --> 00:14:53.219
How do you wanna connect?

00:14:53.219 --> 00:14:54.979
And I was like, all right, let's try ODBC.

00:14:54.979 --> 00:14:57.299
And then, of course, it couldn't find the ODBC driver,

00:14:57.299 --> 00:14:59.780
and it really was like, I don't know how to make this work.

00:14:59.780 --> 00:15:04.500
And then finally, this was like a very surprising way

00:15:04.500 --> 00:15:07.419
and good reminder of how creative these LLMs can be.

00:15:07.419 --> 00:15:08.880
Finally, it was like, you know what I'm gonna do?

00:15:08.880 --> 00:15:11.979
I found documentation about the Databricks API.

00:15:11.979 --> 00:15:14.960
I'm just gonna write an R wrapper around that API.

00:15:14.960 --> 00:15:16.400
So for like five minutes,

00:15:16.400 --> 00:15:18.440
Databot just went and wrote its own R package

00:15:18.440 --> 00:15:19.960
for accessing data in Databricks,

00:15:19.960 --> 00:15:22.080
and then gave me a bunch of methods for doing so,

00:15:22.080 --> 00:15:24.320
which is really cool, but not super practical,

00:15:24.320 --> 00:15:25.960
because that package is not portable.

00:15:25.960 --> 00:15:28.260
It's like its own little SDK that it wrote.

00:15:28.260 --> 00:15:29.760
So one of the things that we're working on

00:15:29.760 --> 00:15:32.559
immediately right now is kind of solving

00:15:32.559 --> 00:15:33.919
this zero to one problem.

00:15:33.919 --> 00:15:36.000
If I'm opening one of these tools,

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:38.400
whether it's Positron Assistant or Databot,

00:15:38.400 --> 00:15:41.200
and I wanna connect to data that's not local, right?

00:15:41.200 --> 00:15:44.200
I wanna connect to some data that's in some place,

00:15:44.200 --> 00:15:45.400
making it a lot easier to say,

00:15:45.400 --> 00:15:48.440
hey, help me explore this data that's here,

00:15:48.440 --> 00:15:50.000
the table's called this,

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:52.000
and we'd have the right context and the right understanding

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:54.679
to be able to go and do that without reinventing the wheel,

00:15:54.679 --> 00:15:56.679
which is kind of what we saw previously.

00:15:57.599 --> 00:15:58.799
The last thing I'll point out here,

00:15:58.799 --> 00:16:00.000
and then I'll see what questions we have,

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:03.119
is kind of the flip side of this,

00:16:03.119 --> 00:16:05.479
and this has been brought up a couple of times here

00:16:05.479 --> 00:16:07.520
in the conference as well.

00:16:07.520 --> 00:16:10.039
In addition to these AI sort of assistant tools

00:16:10.039 --> 00:16:12.239
that exist from a developer standpoint,

00:16:12.239 --> 00:16:13.760
we've also created a lot of tools

00:16:14.320 --> 00:16:16.719
that enable you as developers and as data scientists

00:16:16.719 --> 00:16:19.719
to build on top of these AI systems.

00:16:19.719 --> 00:16:20.960
One of those tools that's been brought up

00:16:20.960 --> 00:16:22.640
a couple of times here in the conference

00:16:22.640 --> 00:16:24.119
has been QueryChat.

00:16:24.119 --> 00:16:27.359
So let me just share this kind of example.

00:16:27.359 --> 00:16:30.280
So this is a dashboard written in Shiny

00:16:30.280 --> 00:16:32.479
that we created for this Tour de France data,

00:16:32.479 --> 00:16:34.159
where we have some visualizations

00:16:34.159 --> 00:16:35.359
and some information that we can see,

00:16:35.359 --> 00:16:36.239
and then on the left-hand side,

00:16:36.239 --> 00:16:37.280
we have this chat interface

00:16:37.280 --> 00:16:38.880
where we can ask questions about the data

00:16:38.880 --> 00:16:41.080
or create filters for the data.

00:16:41.080 --> 00:16:43.719
And this is really, like, the way to set this up,

00:16:43.719 --> 00:16:46.479
the way to configure this is remarkably easy

00:16:46.479 --> 00:16:48.440
in terms of there's not a lot of plumbing to do,

00:16:48.440 --> 00:16:50.880
and then you have this really nice, intuitive,

00:16:50.880 --> 00:16:53.400
natural language interface to your data.

00:16:53.400 --> 00:16:54.799
But the other thing that's really great

00:16:54.799 --> 00:16:56.239
is if you build these tools

00:16:56.239 --> 00:16:59.840
on top of enterprise data sources like Snowflake,

00:16:59.840 --> 00:17:01.840
you can get this behavior where I can come in here

00:17:01.840 --> 00:17:03.679
and I can say, okay, show me the writers

00:17:03.679 --> 00:17:05.439
who ever won a stage.

00:17:05.439 --> 00:17:09.040
There's one really glaring inclusion here.

00:17:09.040 --> 00:17:10.160
This is really fuzzy, I'm sorry,

00:17:10.199 --> 00:17:12.160
but this is Lance Armstrong,

00:17:12.160 --> 00:17:14.439
notoriously famous for doping his way

00:17:14.439 --> 00:17:16.719
to several Tour de France titles.

00:17:16.719 --> 00:17:19.359
So, like, officially, he's won zero, right?

00:17:19.359 --> 00:17:22.560
But in this data, it shows that he's won 24 stages.

00:17:22.560 --> 00:17:24.280
So what we did is we went into Snowflake

00:17:24.280 --> 00:17:26.079
and we wrote this filter that says,

00:17:26.079 --> 00:17:28.640
hey, certain users actually cannot see records

00:17:28.640 --> 00:17:30.560
from doped cyclists.

00:17:30.560 --> 00:17:33.680
Well, if one of those users goes to this dashboard

00:17:33.680 --> 00:17:35.040
that we have running on Posit Connect,

00:17:35.040 --> 00:17:36.119
and they log in and they say,

00:17:36.119 --> 00:17:40.680
hey, like, tell me how many stages Lance Armstrong won,

00:17:40.680 --> 00:17:44.280
they don't see 24, the answer they get back is zero.

00:17:44.280 --> 00:17:45.959
And it's not because the dashboard's different,

00:17:45.959 --> 00:17:48.599
it's because their permission on the data is different.

00:17:48.599 --> 00:17:53.439
So this sort of intersection of Posit tools

00:17:53.439 --> 00:17:54.880
and enterprise data sources

00:17:54.880 --> 00:17:56.319
gives you this really flexible way

00:17:56.319 --> 00:18:00.660
to build resources and tools using agentic helpers

00:18:00.660 --> 00:18:04.979
that also adhere to enterprise best data practices.

00:18:04.979 --> 00:18:06.300
People that shouldn't see certain data

00:18:06.300 --> 00:18:08.619
don't see it through your application, right?

00:18:08.619 --> 00:18:11.459
The same filters, the same restrictions apply

00:18:11.459 --> 00:18:13.219
on the underlying data when they come in here

00:18:13.219 --> 00:18:14.060
to Posit Connect.

00:18:14.060 --> 00:18:15.099
About one minute,

00:18:15.099 --> 00:18:19.619
so you'll be on the Positron Lounge channel in Discord.

00:18:19.619 --> 00:18:20.439
Yes.

00:18:21.579 --> 00:18:23.699
Okay, so I will keep an eye if there's questions

00:18:23.699 --> 00:18:26.660
on the Positron Lounge channel inside of Discord,

00:18:26.660 --> 00:18:28.339
and then I'm happy, I think we've got maybe a minute

00:18:28.339 --> 00:18:29.180
for questions here.

00:18:29.180 --> 00:18:31.180
So I'll wrap up and see if there's any questions

00:18:31.180 --> 00:18:32.020
with this group.

00:18:33.420 --> 00:18:34.260
Thank you.

00:18:34.619 --> 00:18:35.459
Thank you.

00:18:35.459 --> 00:18:36.300
Thank you.

00:18:36.300 --> 00:18:37.119
Thank you.

00:18:37.119 --> 00:18:37.959
Thank you.

00:18:37.959 --> 00:18:40.020
I'm gonna stop with one question right now.

00:18:40.020 --> 00:18:40.859
George has asked,

00:18:40.859 --> 00:18:42.739
in terms of cost, generally speaking,

00:18:42.739 --> 00:18:45.020
is it more efficient to run data wrangling

00:18:45.020 --> 00:18:47.819
and analysis tasks in Positron

00:18:47.819 --> 00:18:50.180
or RStudio versus cloud environment?

00:18:51.619 --> 00:18:55.300
I think cost-wise, it's an interesting question

00:18:55.300 --> 00:18:56.619
because these cloud environments,

00:18:56.619 --> 00:18:57.500
depending on what it is, right?

00:18:57.500 --> 00:19:00.660
Snowflake and Databricks both charge by compute unit,

00:19:00.660 --> 00:19:02.660
and so you do incur some costs there.

00:19:02.699 --> 00:19:04.540
But it's less of a cost trade-off, I think,

00:19:04.540 --> 00:19:07.859
in my opinion, and it's more of a performance trade-off,

00:19:07.859 --> 00:19:09.579
and just like a security thing.

00:19:09.579 --> 00:19:11.939
In a lot of cases, security doesn't want data

00:19:11.939 --> 00:19:13.979
being shuffled around into local environments

00:19:13.979 --> 00:19:15.300
and then back into the cloud.

00:19:15.300 --> 00:19:17.540
They want data to stay within the security boundary

00:19:17.540 --> 00:19:20.939
of whatever warehouse you've selected to use,

00:19:20.939 --> 00:19:25.260
and in a lot of cases, that data's gonna be large enough

00:19:25.260 --> 00:19:27.140
that moving it locally and then trying to work with it there

00:19:27.140 --> 00:19:28.939
is gonna end up becoming a bottleneck.

00:19:28.939 --> 00:19:30.459
So just keeping it in the warehouse, I think,

00:19:30.459 --> 00:19:32.380
is typically best practice.

00:19:33.099 --> 00:19:34.380
If it's small enough data that you want to move it locally,

00:19:34.380 --> 00:19:36.979
I think that's a conversation to have internally,

00:19:36.979 --> 00:19:38.459
maybe with security and others,

00:19:38.459 --> 00:19:42.380
but in many cases, this is a fairly simple toy example,

00:19:42.380 --> 00:19:44.140
but when you're dealing with terabytes of data

00:19:44.140 --> 00:19:45.780
that might be in these warehouses,

00:19:45.780 --> 00:19:47.500
then letting the warehouse do the heavy lifting

00:19:47.500 --> 00:19:48.540
makes a lot of sense.

00:19:50.219 --> 00:19:53.459
Do we have a question from the room?

00:19:53.459 --> 00:19:54.579
Well, I have a question.

00:19:54.579 --> 00:19:55.900
Oh, go ahead.

00:19:55.900 --> 00:19:57.459
I was just wondering,

00:19:57.459 --> 00:20:01.140
given that the cloud's a strong system, it's using cloud,

00:20:01.140 --> 00:20:05.619
will cloud have visibility to the Snowflake

00:20:05.619 --> 00:20:08.140
connection credentials, because you're kind of seeing

00:20:08.140 --> 00:20:10.420
that as potentially being a security issue?

00:20:10.420 --> 00:20:12.939
Yeah, so that's kind of part of what we're starting

00:20:12.939 --> 00:20:16.619
to think through right now, is how do we expose,

00:20:17.579 --> 00:20:21.939
excuse me, how do we expose metadata from these connections

00:20:21.939 --> 00:20:24.339
so that the suggestions and the code that's written

00:20:24.339 --> 00:20:28.140
is accurate in terms of column names and references

00:20:28.140 --> 00:20:29.180
and things like that,

00:20:29.180 --> 00:20:31.339
without giving free reign of credentials, right?

00:20:31.339 --> 00:20:33.099
So we're very conscious of that.

00:20:33.099 --> 00:20:35.540
We recognize that there's a high level of risk

00:20:35.540 --> 00:20:38.660
in exposing these tools to enterprise data platforms,

00:20:38.660 --> 00:20:40.380
so we're working to approach it the right way,

00:20:40.380 --> 00:20:43.020
where you can control what sort of context

00:20:43.020 --> 00:20:44.699
is passed into these tools,

00:20:44.699 --> 00:20:48.180
and you're not just passing a free pass

00:20:48.180 --> 00:20:49.500
into your enterprise data.

00:20:50.500 --> 00:20:51.900
Yeah.

00:20:51.900 --> 00:20:53.819
All right, we gotta get ready for the next session,

00:20:53.819 --> 00:20:54.939
but thank you so much.

00:20:54.939 --> 00:20:55.780
Thank you, everyone.

00:20:55.979 --> 00:20:56.900
Thank you.

00:20:56.900 --> 00:20:57.699
Thank you, guys.

